<p><b>Clarence Thomas</b> (born June 23, 1948) is an American <a href="/wiki/Jurist" title="Jurist">jurist</a>. He has served as an <a href="/wiki/Associate_Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States">Associate Justice</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Supreme Court of the United States">Supreme Court of the United States</a> since 1991, the second <a href="/wiki/African_American" title="African American">African American</a> to serve on the nation's highest court (after <a href="/wiki/Associate_Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States">Justice</a> <a href="/wiki/Thurgood_Marshall" title="Thurgood Marshall">Thurgood Marshall</a>, whom he succeeded). Appointed by <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">President</a> <a href="/wiki/George_H._W._Bush" title="George H. W. Bush">George H. W. Bush</a>, Thomas's career on the Supreme Court has seen him take a <a href="/wiki/Judicial_philosophy#Judicial_Conservative" title="Judicial philosophy">judicially conservative</a> approach, adhering to the principle of <a href="/wiki/Originalism" title="Originalism">originalism</a>. Because he believes in upholding the <a href="/wiki/Original_meaning" title="Original meaning">original meaning</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Constitution" title="United States Constitution">Constitution</a> and statutes, he looks to the exact phrasing of a law's text as the surest guide to its meaning.</p>
