<li id="cite_note-souter_biography-28"><b><a href="#cite_ref-souter_biography_28-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFTinsley_E._Yarbrough2009">Tinsley E. Yarbrough (2005). <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=mvV0cVeWVmUC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=david+souter+%22home+run%22&amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;cad=0" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=mvV0cVeWVmUC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=david+souter+%22home+run%22&amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;cad=0" rel="nofollow">"David Hackett Souter: Traditional Republican on the Rehnquist Court"</a>. Oxford University Press<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=mvV0cVeWVmUC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=david+souter+%22home+run%22&amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;cad=0" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=mvV0cVeWVmUC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=david+souter+%22home+run%22&amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;cad=0" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=mvV0cVeWVmUC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=david+souter+%22home+run%22&amp;source=gbs_summary_s&amp;cad=0</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-06-27</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=David+Hackett+Souter%3A+Traditional+Republican+on+the+Rehnquist+Court&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Tinsley+E.+Yarbrough&amp;rft.au=Tinsley+E.+Yarbrough&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DmvV0cVeWVmUC%26printsec%3Dfrontcover%26dq%3Ddavid%2Bsouter%2B%2522home%2Brun%2522%26source%3Dgbs_summary_s%26cad%3D0&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Clarence_Thomas"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-29"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29" title="">^</a></b> It is routine for nominees, at all levels of the Federal judiciary, to refuse to discuss cases during their confirmation hearings that might come before them if they are confirmed. <a href="/wiki/Bill_Clinton" title="Bill Clinton">Clinton</a> appointed Associate Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Steven_Breyer&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Steven Breyer (page does not exist)">Steven Breyer</a>, who both refused to discuss <i>Roe</i> before the Judiciary Committee, even though Ginsburg has worked for years for the <a href="/wiki/ACLU" title="ACLU" class="mw-redirect">ACLU</a> defending it. Despite this nearly universal refusal of nominees to discuss hot button issues such as <i>Roe</i>, members of the Senate Judiciary Committee nearly always try to draw the nominee's view out during confirmation hearings.</li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://opinionjournal.com/diary/?id=85000412" class="external text" title="http://opinionjournal.com/diary/?id=85000412" rel="nofollow"><i>Wall Street Journal</i></a></li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31" title="">^</a></b> "My Grandfather's Son, A Memoir," Thomas, Clarence (New York: HarperCollins, 2007), p. 238</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32" title="">^</a></b> In particular, the questioning by <a href="/wiki/Arlen_Specter" title="Arlen Specter">Senator Specter</a> was intense. See Morrison, Toni. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?num=100&amp;hl=en&amp;safe=off&amp;rlz=1G1GGLQ_ENUS262&amp;q=%22intense%20questioning%22%20clarence%20anita%20specter&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;sa=N&amp;tab=wp" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?num=100&amp;hl=en&amp;safe=off&amp;rlz=1G1GGLQ_ENUS262&amp;q=%22intense%20questioning%22%20clarence%20anita%20specter&amp;um=1&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;sa=N&amp;tab=wp" rel="nofollow">“Race-ing Justice, En-gendering Power,”</a> page 55 (Pantheon Books 1992). After the questioning, Specter said that, "the testimony of Professor Hill in the morning was flat out perjury", and that "she specifically changed it in the afternoon when confronted with the possibility of being contradicted." See <a href="http://www.gpoaccess.gov/congress/senate/judiciary/sh102-1084pt4/227-234.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.gpoaccess.gov/congress/senate/judiciary/sh102-1084pt4/227-234.pdf" rel="nofollow">transcript</a>, page 230.</li>
